To add a delay or pause in JavaScript, you can use the `setTimeout` function or `async/await` with `setTimeout`.

Using `setTimeout`:
```javascript
console.log("Before delay");
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("After delay");
}, 2000); // Delay of 2000 milliseconds (2 seconds)
console.log("End of code");
```
This will output:
```
Before delay
End of code
After delay (after 2 seconds)
```

Using `async/await` with `setTimeout` (requires using an async function):
```javascript
const delay = (ms) => new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));

async function doSomething() {
  console.log("Before delay");
  await delay(2000); // Delay of 2000 milliseconds (2 seconds)
  console.log("After delay");
  console.log("End of code");
}

doSomething();
```
This will output:
```
Before delay
(after 2 seconds)
After delay
End of code
```

In the second example, the `delay` function is a utility function that returns a promise that resolves after the specified delay. By using `await` with `delay(2000)`, the function execution will pause for 2 seconds before continuing with the next line of code.

Choose the method that suits your needs based on the context of your code.
